<br>
However, they have failed to recognize one more factor in the game that is inherently debilitating; the idea of mana transference.<br>
<br>
When this ability is bestowed upon any class, you will basically DIRECTLY pit that class in terms of usefulness with all other classes that use mana. Then it comes down to one simple question: Who can better make use of that mana? If it's the mana transferer, then the ability is often-times unused and just becomes something to harp on when you have a surplus and others are low. It may also be good in specific situations where a particular spell type is needed over another. Otherwise, mana transference just reflects upon the inferior mana usage of one class as compared to another.<br>
<br>
Now, looking through all the fancy spells with all the twists and turns put in over the years... I still see only 2 types that need be sustained over the course of the battle requiring vastly larger amounts of mana than any others: damage spells and healing spells. That's basically what it comes down to. Feel free to disagree with me, but that's what I've concluded until I hear a better argument. Therefore, the two classes who get the most benefit out of mana transference will be the wizard and the cleric. All other classes are inferior in terms of mana usage during battle and therefore, if they get any adequate type of mana transference, it would be better to serve up their mana then to use it themselves.<br>
<br>
Therefore, I think that if mana transference should have existed, then it should have been given to clerics and wizards because for any other class, it would be better to use their &quot;adequate&quot; mana transference to contribute to the damage and healing spell pool rather than to waste it on themselves. If wizards and clerics had it on the other hand, they can pick and choose when to use the mana and when to transfer depending on such things as shortage of 1 class or the other, type of encounter, surplus of mana, etc...<br>
<br>
Sadly, the above is not the case for then... things would be much easier to fix and/or control. Mana Transference does exist but it exists for other classes (like mages). Mages not only got mana transference but they got it at such a rate that it could effectively turn into &quot;infinite mana&quot; as Verant puts it which overrides the usefulness of such things like Necro twitching.<br>
<br>
What Verant probably had in mind for mana transference was just a handy tool to siphon off surplus mana, or to give mana to those who can handle particular situations very well, or to help others in mana intensive activities like buffing or rezzing, etc... Basically, I doubted it was supposed to be more than just a secondary class tool. What they fail to realize is the min/max nature of the game evidenced particularly at the higher levels. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uniden.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Niden</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Arch Mage</span><br>  Posts: 355<br> <font color=#333333>(10/10/02 6:03:22 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=365.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Nod.</span><hr size=1> You're exactly correct about the nature of mana transference, which is precisely why the 'adjustment' to trans rods will do very little to solve the problem of magicians being 'rod whores'.  It simply solves the problem of people being able to create unlimited amounts of mana, which is a balance problem that Verant is concerned with.  Don't for a moment think that they were particularly concerned about mage class balance when they decided to remove trans rods. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :| --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/indifferent.gif ALT=":|"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
